13<br>present{{efn|Pritzker's first term expires on January 9, 2023.}}\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|[[2018 Illinois gubernatorial election|2018]]\n|bgcolor=\"{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Stratton, Juliana\"|[[Juliana Stratton]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Illinois state legislatures]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n;General\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_illinois.html |title=Illinois: Past Governors Bios|publisher=[[National Governors Association]] |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/illinois_bluebook/officialsroster.pdf | title=Illinois Blue Book | publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]] | pages=359-360 | accessdate=April 26, 2018}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Constitutions\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://archive.org/details/constitutionofst00inilli | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1818}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/isl2/id/211 | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1848}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924024668232 | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1870}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.ilga.gov/commission/lrb/conmain.htm | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1970}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{Governors of Illinois}}\n{{Illinois}}\n{{Lists of US Governors}}\n{{Illinois year nav}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Governors Of Illinois, List Of}}\n[[Category:Governors of Illinois|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of Illinois politicians]]\n[[Category:Lists of state governors of the United States|Illinois]]\n[[Category:Political history of Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Governor\n|body            = Illinois\n|insignia        = Seal of Illinois.svg\n|insigniasize    = 110px\n|insigniacaption = [[Flag and seal of Illinois|Seal of the State of Illinois]]\n|flag            = Flag of Illinois.svg\n|flagborder      = yes\n|flagcaption     = [[Flag and seal of Illinois|Flag of Illinois]]\n|image           = JB Pritzker at Gold Star Mothers Luncheon (cropped).jpg\n|imagesize       = 200px\n|incumbent       = [[J. B. Pritzker]]\n|incumbentsince  = January 14, 2019\n|residence       = [[Illinois Governor's Mansion]]\n|termlength      = Four years, no term limits\n|formation       = {{start date|1818|10|06}}\n|inaugural       = [[Shadrach Bond]]\n|salary          = $177,412 (2015)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://knowledgecenter.csg.org/kc/content/governors-salaries-2015 | title=Governors\u2019 Salaries, 2015 | publisher=The Council of State Governments | date=June 25, 2013 | accessdate=January 9, 2016 }}</ref>{{note|salary|\u03b1}}\n|website         = {{URL|https://www2.illinois.gov/gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[Governor of Illinois]] is the [[Head of government|chief executive]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. The [[Governor (United States)|governor]] is the head of the [[Executive (government)|executive branch]] of [[Government of Illinois|Illinois's state government]] and is charged with enforcing state laws. The governor has the power to either approve or [[veto]] bills passed by the [[Illinois General Assembly|Illinois Legislature]], to convene the legislature, and to grant [[pardon]]s, except in cases of [[impeachment]].<ref>IL Const. art. V</ref> The governor is also the [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[U.S. state|state's]] [[Illinois National Guard|military forces]].\n\nSince becoming a state in 1818, 42 people have served as governor of Illinois; before statehood, it had only 1 territorial governor, [[Ninian Edwards]]. The longest-serving governor was [[James R. Thompson]], who was elected four times to a term lasting 14 years, from 1977 to 1991. Only one governor, [[Richard J. Oglesby]], has served multiple separate terms, having been elected in 1864, 1872, and 1884. \n\nOne governor, [[Rod Blagojevich]], was impeached and removed from office in 2009. Unique among the states is the notable fact that four of Illinois' seven governors between 1961 and 2009 were imprisoned for various forms of corruption while in office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daily-journal.com/news/local/of-illinois-last-governors-went-to-prison/article_570fe718-8c52-5db3-8bc5-13d49974d930.html|title=4 of Illinois' last 7 governors went to prison |website=Kankakee Daily Journal| date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2019-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/archive/8973798/|title=4 out of previous 7 Illinois governors (Kerner, Walker, Ryan and Blagojevich) went to prison |website=WLS-TV Eyewitness News |date=2013-01-13 |accessdate=2019-06-14}}</ref>  The current governor is [[J. B. Pritzker]], who took office on January 14, 2019.\n\n==Governors==\n\n===Governor of the Territory of Illinois===\n[[Illinois Territory]] was formed on March 1, 1809, from [[Indiana Territory]]. It had only one governor appointed by the [[President of the United States]] before it became a state, [[Ninian Edwards]]. From March to June 1809, Territorial Secretary [[Nathaniel Pope]] served as acting governor until Edwards arrived in Illinois.<ref>Robert P. Howard (1988), ''Mostly Good and Competent Men: Illinois Governors, 1818\u20131988,'' Illinois Issues and the Illinois State Historical Society, 39\u201340.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Governor of the Territory of Illinois\n!scope=\"col\"|Portrait\n!scope=\"col\"|Governor\n!scope=\"col\"|Term in office\n!scope=\"col\"|Appointed by\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|[[File:Ninian.Edwards.png|75px]]\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Ninian Edwards]]\n|align=\"center\"|March 1, 1809<br />&ndash;<br />October 6, 1818\n|[[James Madison]]\n|}\n\n===Governors of the State of Illinois===\nIllinois was [[Admission to the Union|admitted to the Union]] on December 3, 1818, consisting of the southern portion of Illinois Territory; the remainder was assigned to [[Michigan Territory]].<ref>{{usstat|3|536}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Constitution of Illinois|Illinois Constitution]], ratified in 1818, provided that a governor be elected every 4 years<ref>1818 Const. art. III, \u00a7 2</ref> for a term starting on the first Monday in the December following an election.<ref>1818 Const. art. III, \u00a7 3</ref> The constitution of 1848 moved the start of the term to the second Monday in January starting in 1849, thus shortening the term won in the 1844 election to 2 years.<ref name=\"1848const-art4-sec3\">1848 Const. art. IV, \u00a7 3</ref> Governors were not allowed to succeed themselves<ref>1818 Const. art. III, \u00a7 3</ref> until the 1870 constitution, which removed this limit.\n\nThe office of [[Lieutenant Governor of Illinois|lieutenant governor]] was created in the first constitution,<ref>1818 Const. art. III, \u00a7 13</ref> to exercise the power of governor if that office becomes vacant.<ref>1818 Const. art. III, \u00a7 18</ref> The 1848 constitution changed this to say the power \"devolves\" upon the lieutenant governor in case of a vacancy.<ref>1848 Const. art. IV, \u00a7 19</ref> The current constitution of 1970 made it so that, in the event of a vacancy, the lieutenant becomes governor,<ref name=\"const-art5sec6\">IL Const. art. V, \u00a7 6</ref> and the governor and lieutenant governor are now elected on the same [[ticket (election)|ticket]].<ref>IL Const. art. V, \u00a7 4</ref> If the governor feels seriously impeded in performing their job, they can inform the [[Illinois Secretary of State|secretary of state]] and the next in the line of succession, who becomes acting governor until the governor can resume office.<ref name=\"const-art5sec6\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Governors of the State of Illinois\n!scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\"|{{abbr|No.|Number}}{{efn|Based on the official site labeling Bruce Rauner as the 42nd governor,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www2.illinois.gov/gov/about/Pages/AbouttheGovernor.aspx | title=About the Governor | publisher=State of Illinos | accessdate=April 25, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426081238/https://www2.illinois.gov/gov/about/Pages/AbouttheGovernor.aspx | archive-date=2018-04-26 | url-status=dead }}</ref> it is assumed the official numbering includes repeat governors only once; subsequent terms are marked with their original number italicized.}}\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\"|Governor\n!scope=\"col\"|Term in office\n!scope=\"col\"|Party\n!scope=\"col\"|Election\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"|[[Lieutenant Governor of Illinois|Lt. Governor]]{{efn|Lieutenant governors represented the same party as their governor unless noted.}}{{efn|When the lieutenant governor is serving as governor, the Illinois Blue Book considers the president pro tempore of the senate to be acting lieutenant governor. However, this only applies to acting lieutenant governors before 1883; after that, there are no acting lieutenant governors noted, and instead these are marked vacant. It is unknown why this changed; the constitution does not appear to have any relevant changes around that time.<ref>Illinois Blue Book, p. 360</ref>}}\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|1\n|data-sort-value=\"Bond, Shadrach\"|[[File:Shadrach.Bond.png|75px]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Independent (United States)/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Shadrach Bond]]\n|{{dts|October 6, 1818}}<br />&ndash;<br />December 5, 1822<br><small>(term limited)</small>\n|[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n|[[1818 Illinois gubernatorial election|1818]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Independent (United States)/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n|data-sort-value=\"Menard, Pierre\"|[[Pierre Menard]]\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|2\n|data-sort-value=\"Coles, Edward\"|[[File:Edward.Coles.png|75px]]\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Edward Coles]]\n|{{dts|December 5, 1822}}<br />&ndash;<br />December 6, 1826<br><small>(term limited)</small>\n|[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n|[[1822 Illinois gubernatorial election|1822]]\n|data-sort-value=\"Hubbard, Adolphus\"|[[Adolphus Hubbard]]\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|3\n|data-sort-value=\"Edwards, Ninian\"|[[File:Ninian.Edwards.png|75px]]\n|bgcolor=\"{{Democratic-Republican Party/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Ninian Edwards]]\n|{{dts|December 6, 1826}}<br />&ndash;<br />December 6, 1830<br><small>(term limited)</small>\n|[[Democratic-Republican Party|Adams-Clay<br />Republican]]\n|[[1826 Illinois gubernatorial election|1826]]\n|bgcolor=\"{{Democratic-Republican Party/meta/color}}\"|&nbsp;\n|data-sort-value=\"Kinney, William\"|[[William Kinney]]\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"|4\n|rowspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"Reynolds, John\"|[[File:John.Reynolds.png|75px]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{National Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}\"|\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[John Reynolds (Illinois politician)|John Reynolds]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{dts|December 6, 1830}}<br />&ndash;<br />November 17, 1834<br><small>(resigned)</small>{{efn|Reynolds resigned to take elected seat in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_illinois/col2-content/main-content-list/title_reynolds_john.default.html | title=John Reynolds | publisher=[[National Governors Association]] | accessdate=June 1, 2018}}</ref>}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[National Republican Party (United States)|National Republican]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1830 Illinois gubernatorial election|1830]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Casey, Zadok\"|[[Zadok Casey]]<br /><small>(resigned March 1, 1833)</small>\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|data-sort-value=\"Ewing, William\"|[[William Lee D. Ewing]]<br /><small>(acting)</small>\n|- style=\"height:2em;\"\n|5\n|data-sort-value=