)/meta/color}}\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Stratton, Juliana\"|[[Juliana Stratton]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Illinois state legislatures]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n;General\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_illinois.html |title=Illinois: Past Governors Bios|publisher=[[National Governors Association]] |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/illinois_bluebook/officialsroster.pdf | title=Illinois Blue Book | publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]] | pages=359-360 | accessdate=April 26, 2018}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Constitutions\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://archive.org/details/constitutionofst00inilli | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1818}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/isl2/id/211 | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1848}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924024668232 | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1870}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.ilga.gov/commission/lrb/conmain.htm | title=Constitution of the State of Illinois | year=1970}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{Governors of Illinois}}\n{{Illinois}}\n{{Lists of US Governors}}\n{{Illinois year nav}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Governors Of Illinois, List Of}}\n[[Category:Governors of Illinois|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of Illinois politicians]]\n[[Category:Lists of state governors of the United States|Illinois]]\n[[Category:Political history of Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_governors_of_Illinois"}
{"title_page": "Josh Joplin Group", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2010}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Josh Joplin Group\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = Group_or_Band\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132002\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[Folk Rock]]<br />[[Americana music{{!}}]]<br />[[Rock music|Rock]]<br />\n| label            = [[Independent music|Independent]], SMG, [[Artemis Records|Artemis]] [[Sony]], [[Epic]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}\n| associated_acts  = \n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = [[Josh Joplin]]<br />Geoff Melkonian<br />Jason Buecker<br />Allen Broyles<br />Deeds Davis<br />[[Ani Cordero]]<br />Eric Taylor\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Josh Joplin Group''' was an Atlanta, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]-based [[Rock music|rock]] band led by [[singer-songwriter]] [[Josh Joplin]]. Initially a trio, Joplin hired Geoff Melkonian (bass/viola/vocals) and Jason Buecker (drums/percussion/vocals) to accompany him to play shows together. They simply called themselves Josh Joplin Band<ref>{{Cite news|last=Walton|first=A. Scott|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  In late 1995 they began pre-production on their first album together. Recorded at Furies Studios with producer Ed Burdell ([[Magnapop]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-burdell-mn0000144299|title=All Music|last=Burdell|first=Ed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Projector Head<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=DeVault|first=Russ|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Guide To Music Midtown|date=May 3, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was released, January 6, 1996<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Concert Preview|date=January 5, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  Based on local critical success and some airplay on local radio <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Peach-Jam-1997/release/8495065|title=Various - Peach Jam 1997|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Joplin, Buecker, and Melkonian, began touring vigorously. Starting in the south, continuing through the northeast, and beyond<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gambill|first=Rex|url=|title=Projector Head: Josh Joplin Band|date=December 27, 1996|work=The Coschocton Tribune, Coshocton Ohio|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  \n\n''Boxing Nostalgic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Band-Boxing-Nostalgic/release/11443808|title=Josh Joplin Band - Boxing Nostalgic|last=Joplin|first=Josh|date=|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430711/shawn-mullins-inks-deal-with-josh-joplin-band/|title=Shawn Mullins Inks Deal With Josh Joplin Band|last=News Staff|first=Mtv|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Music Around Town|date=August 1, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>was their self produced sophomore effort. It was released April 6th, 1997 to a sold out show at the Cotton Club<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Joplin Learning Reality Of Recording Business|date=April 4, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The album introduced piano to their sound and Allen Broyles who played on the record would join the band that same year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=In Concert This Weekend|date=May 21, 1999|work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The band continued touring and opening shows for [[Jump, Little Children]], [[Five Eight (band)|Five Eight]], [[The Innocence Mission]], [[Ben Harper]], [[Neil Finn]], Nathan Sheppard, Kitty Snyder, among others. \n\nIn 1998, having played the [[Roxy Theatre (Atlanta)]] opening for [[Shawn Mullins]] the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated songwriter of [[Lullaby (Shawn Mullins song)|Lullaby]], the band discussed making their third album with their friend and Mullins signed on as the producer hiring  [[Anthony J. Resta discography|Anthony J. Resta]] to create the beats and programming for it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/useful-music-mw0000112721/credits|title=Useful Music Credits|last=Resta|first=Anthony J.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  He would later release the album entitled, [[Useful Music]], on his own SMG label.<ref name=\":2\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=New and Notable Releases|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>   Shortly after its release, Jason Buecker was replaced on drums by [[Ani Cordero]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wamc.org/post/rogovoy-report-10617|title=WAMC Midday Magazine|last=Rogovoy|first=Seth|date=October 17, 2017|website=WAMC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> then Eric Taylor who drummed for legendary dream pop founders, [[Seely (band)|Seely]] (on [[Too Pure]] Records)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/91118-Seely|title=Seely|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.  Deeds Davis was added to play lead guitar and sing. \n\nThe band was managed briefly by [[Nettwerk]] Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldredge|first=Richard L.|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=August 16, 1999|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> before making a slight name change to Josh Joplin Group when [[Artemis Records]] headed by legendary industry moguls [[Danny Goldberg]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Boyce|first=Kevin|url=|title=King Midas|date=January 23,  2003|work=CMJ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Daniel Glass]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://creativeloafing.com/content-159675-paper-tiger|title=Paper Tiger|last=Sarig|first=Roni|date=August 1, 2001|website=Creative Loafing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. signed them to their label.  They were picked up by [[Indigo Girls]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Black|first=Alan|url=https://smartech.gatech.edu/bitstream/handle/1853/7873/music_midtown-2001-06-01.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=Music Midtown 2001|date=June 1, 2001|work=Recaps|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and [[Matthew Sweet]] manager, Russell Carter. \n\nThe Artemis re-release would feature an alternative version of Joplin's ballad, I've Changed. It was lavishly produced by [[Peter Collins (record producer)|Peter Collins]] at Nashville's [[Ocean Way Recording]] studio, with [[Kenny Aronoff]] playing drums. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenny-aronoff-mn0000081149/credits|title=Kenny Aronoff Discography|last=Aronoff|first=Kenny|date=|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/useful-music-mw0000112721/credits.|title=Camera One|last=Music|first=Useful|date=January 1, 2001|website=AllMusic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A slightly more successful collaboration came when ex-[[The Modern Lovers|Modern Lover]] / [[Talking Heads|Talking Head,]] [[Jerry Harrison]] was brought on produce the opening track, Matter and Joplin's new song, Camera One, which hadn't been previously released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyvault.com/toc.php5?review=1827|title=Daily Vault|last=Warburg|first=Jason|date=February 15, 2002|website=Daily Vault|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=jerry+harrison+and+Josh+Joplin+group&source=bl&ots=pV-WQ4xtHb&sig=ACfU3U2MzvZzTDuj4LH4VxMi-1n0E1WnFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj15PDHw97oAhUJLs0KHW4UCwYQ6AEwB3oECA4QKQ#v=onepage&q=jerry%20harrison%20and%20Josh%20Joplin%20group&f=false|title=Billboard|date=December 16, 2000|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Group-Camera-One-2/release/3038187|title=Useful Music Camera One +2|last=Group|first=Josh Joplin|date=2000|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe album came out in January 30, 2001<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sperounes|first=Sandra|url=https://edmontonjournal.com|title=Ten On Tuesday|date=January 27, 2001|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindquist|first=David|url=https://www.indystar.com|title=Joplin Spins Musical Tales|date=October 11, 2001|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>to strong reviews<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Serves Up Useful Music|date=December 16, 2001|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=Now|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 1, 2001|website=Now Toronto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and sold over 100,000 records in its first week.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schwartz|first=Daylle Deanna|title=Start And Run Your Own Record Label|publisher=Billboard Books|year=2003|isbn=0-8230-8433-7|location=NY, NY|pages=151}}</ref> It's single, \"Camera One,\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popradiotop20.com/Year/RR-HAC-2001-Year.htm|title=Hot AC Chart 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> was the first independent release to go [[List of Billboard number-one adult alternative singles of the 2000s#2000|number-one]] at Triple A radio <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Billboard_number-one_adult_alternative_singles_of_the_2000s|title=List Of Billboard #1adult alternative singles|last=Company|first=Neilson|date=March 3, 2001|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>and went to number 22 on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 chart in 2001. It won the \"Single Of The Year\" award by the [[American Association of Independent Music]]. Useful Music songs were featured in many of the top rated shows of the time, including [[Party of Five]], [[Dawson's Creek]], [[Northern Exposure]], and Camera One was a feature of an episode of the comedy series ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.\n\nJosh Joplin Group toured America, Mexico, Canada, Australia, and all of Europe. They played shows with countless bands, and artists including [[Travis (band)|Travis,]] [[Old 97's]], [[Matthew Sweet]],  [[Uncle Green]], [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse,]] [[Pink (singer)|Pink,]] [[Smoke (American band)|Smoke,]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Harrison|first=Shane|url=|title=99x Main Stage Preview Have Your Cake|date=September 17, 1999|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gincel|first=Richard|url=|title=College Night at The High Museum|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and had finished performing a German festival in Cologne, when [[Green Day]] burned the drums and stage. The band has also appeared on [[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]], [[Late Show with David Letterman]], [[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]], [[The Panel (Australian TV series)]], [[The Mike Bullard Show]], [[Viva (TV station)|Viva TV (Germany)]], [[MTV]], [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owens|first=Clay|url=https://www.stardem.com|title=The Pursuit Of Happiness|date=January 11, 2008|work=The Star-Democrat|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June of 2002, Josh Joplin began working on demos for songwriter turned producer, [[Fountains of Wayne]]'s [[Adam Schlesinger]]. Schlesinger was tapped to produce the groups sophomore Artemis release. He recorded 12 songs acoustically at [[Stratosphere Sound]], (owned by Schlesinger and [[James Iha]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513906/a-studio-a-smashing-pumpkin-can-call-home/|title=A Studio A Smashing Pumpkin Can Call Home|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|date=April 30, 1999|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  And although the timing didn't work out for the two to work together, Josh and the group, sans Davis, did end up recording   ''[[The Future That Was]].''<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scarrone|first=John|url=|title=Future That Was' One Of 2002's Best|date=January 7, 2003|work=Poughkeepsie Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with Atlanta producer, Rob Gal and engineers, John Holbrook and Rudyard Lee Cullers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rob-gal-mn0000828329/credits|title=The Future That Was|last=Gal|first=Rob|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-holbrook-mn0000226375|title=The Future That Was|last=Holbrook|first=John|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rudyard-lee-cullers-mn0000527241|title=The Future That Was|last=Cullers|first=Rudyard Lee|date=June 1, 2002|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at Stratosphere.  On this record, the musical styles were similarly varied, ranging from slow piano- and acoustic guitar-driven pop to upbeat keyboard- and electric guitar-based rock.\n\n''The Future That Was'' received critical acclaim<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=5165&name=Josh+Joplin+Group|title=Robert Christgau Dean Of American Rock Critics|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=September 9, 2003|website=Robert Christgau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Goings On About Town|date=November 18, 2002|work=The New Yorker|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/josh-joplin/josh-joplin-group-the-future-that-was/|title=The Future That Was Review|last=Moye|first=Jay|date=April 1, 2003|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Knodel|first=Lisa|url=|title=The Future That Was (Rocked!)|date=October 4, 2002|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldridge|first=Richard|url=|title=Joplin Letting A Little Optimism Be Heard|date=September 23, 2002|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Fuller|first=Cam|url=|title=Joplin's Insight Raises The Flesh|date=April 10, 2002|work=Star Phoenix|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Leslie|first=Karl|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Future That Was Review|date=November 28, 2002|work=St. Cloud Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/josh-joplin/|title=Josh Joplin|last=Kreicbergs|first=John|date=October 31, 2002|website=The Pitch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>but it sold poorly and Artemis released dropped the band from their contract.  Artemis released two singles from the album, \"I Am Not the Only Cowboy\" and \"Wonder Wheel,\" but neither one took off. In the fall of 2003, the band announced that it was breaking up and would play its final two shows in [[Atlanta]] in December of that year.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Josh Joplin Band===\n\n*''Projector Head''\n** Release Date: January 6,1996\n** Label: Self-released\n*''Boxing Nostalgic''\n** Release Date: April 6, 1997\n** Label: Self-released\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: May 25, 1999\n** Label: SMG Records\n\n===Josh Joplin Group===\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: January 23, 2001\n** Label: [[Artemis Records]], [[Sony Music]] (Europe), [[Epic Records]] (Australia, South Africa)\n*''[[The Future That Was]]''\n** Release Date: September 24, 2002\n** Label: Artemis Records\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2010}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Josh Joplin Group\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = Group_or_Band\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132002\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[Folk Rock]]<br />[[Americana music{{!}}]]<br />[[Rock music|Rock]]<br />\n| label            = [[Independent music|Independent]], SMG, [[Artemis Records|Artemis]] [[Sony]], [[Epic]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}\n| associated_acts  = \n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = [[Josh Joplin]]<br />Geoff Melkonian<br />Jason Buecker<br />Allen Broyles<br />Deeds Davis<br />[[Ani Cordero]]<br />Eric Taylor\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Josh Joplin Group''' was an Atlanta, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]-based [[Rock music|rock]] band led by [[singer-songwriter]] [[Josh Joplin]]. Initially a trio, Joplin hired Geoff Melkonian (bass/viola/vocals) and Jason Buecker (drums/percussion/vocals) to accompany him to play shows together. They simply called themselves Josh Joplin Band<ref>{{Cite news|last=Walton|first=A. Scott|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  In late 1995 they began pre-production on their first album together. Recorded at Furies Studios with producer Ed Burdell ([[Magnapop]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-burdell-mn0000144299|title=All Music|last=Burdell|first=Ed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Projector Head<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=DeVault|first=Russ|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Guide To Music Midtown|date=May 3, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was released, January 6, 1996<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Weekend Preview, Concert Preview|date=January 5, 1996|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  Based on local critical success and some airplay on local radio <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Peach-Jam-1997/release/8495065|title=Various - Peach Jam 1997|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Joplin, Buecker, and Melkonian, began touring vigorously. Starting in the south, continuing through the northeast, and beyond<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gambill|first=Rex|url=|title=Projector Head: Josh Joplin Band|date=December 27, 1996|work=The Coschocton Tribune, Coshocton Ohio|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>.  \n\n''Boxing Nostalgic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Band-Boxing-Nostalgic/release/11443808|title=Josh Joplin Band - Boxing Nostalgic|last=Joplin|first=Josh|date=|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430711/shawn-mullins-inks-deal-with-josh-joplin-band/|title=Shawn Mullins Inks Deal With Josh Joplin Band|last=News Staff|first=Mtv|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Music Around Town|date=August 1, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>was their self produced sophomore effort. It was released April 6th, 1997 to a sold out show at the Cotton Club<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=Joplin Learning Reality Of Recording Business|date=April 4, 1997|work=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The album introduced piano to their sound and Allen Broyles who played on the record would join the band that same year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hamilton|first=Doug|url=|title=In Concert This Weekend|date=May 21, 1999|work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  The band continued touring and opening shows for [[Jump, Little Children]], [[Five Eight (band)|Five Eight]], [[The Innocence Mission]], [[Ben Harper]], Nathan Sheppard, Kitty Snyder, among others. \n\nIn 1998, having played the [[Roxy Theatre (Atlanta)]] opening for [[Shawn Mullins]] the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated songwriter of [[Lullaby (Shawn Mullins song)|Lullaby]], the band discussed making their third album with their friend and Mullins signed on as the producer hiring  [[Anthony J. Resta discography|Anthony J. Resta]] to create the beats and programming for it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/useful-music-mw0000112721/credits|title=Useful Music Credits|last=Resta|first=Anthony J.|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  He would later release the album entitled, [[Useful Music]], on his own SMG label.<ref name=\":2\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=New and Notable Releases|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 2001|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>   Shortly after its release, Jason Buecker was replaced on drums by [[Ani Cordero]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wamc.org/post/rogovoy-report-10617|title=WAMC Midday Magazine|last=Rogovoy|first=Seth|date=October 17, 2017|website=WAMC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> then Eric Taylor who drummed for legendary dream pop founders, [[Seely (band)|Seely]] (on [[Too Pure]] Records)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/91118-Seely|title=Seely|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.  Deeds Davis was added to play lead guitar and sing. \n\nThe band was managed briefly by [[Nettwerk]] Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldredge|first=Richard L.|url=|title=Peach Buzz|date=August 16, 1999|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> before making a slight name change to Josh Joplin Group when [[Artemis Records]] headed by legendary industry moguls [[Danny Goldberg]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Boyce|first=Kevin|url=|title=King Midas|date=January 23,  2003|work=CMJ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Daniel Glass]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://creativeloafing.com/content-159675-paper-tiger|title=Paper Tiger|last=Sarig|first=Roni|date=August 1, 2001|website=Creative Loafing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. signed them to their label.  They were picked up by [[Indigo Girls]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Black|first=Alan|url=https://smartech.gatech.edu/bitstream/handle/1853/7873/music_midtown-2001-06-01.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=Music Midtown 2001|date=June 1, 2001|work=Recaps|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and [[Matthew Sweet]] manager, Russell Carter. \n\nThe Artemis re-release would feature an alternative version of Joplin's ballad, I've Changed. It was lavishly produced by [[Peter Collins (record producer)|Peter Collins]] at Nashville's [[Ocean Way Recording]] studio, with [[Kenny Aronoff]] playing drums. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenny-aronoff-mn0000081149/credits|title=Kenny Aronoff Discography|last=Aronoff|first=Kenny|date=|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  A slightly more successful collaboration came when ex-[[The Modern Lovers|Modern Lover]] / [[Talking Heads|Talking Head,]] [[Jerry Harrison]] was brought on produce the opening track, Matter and Joplin's new song, Camera One, which hadn't been previously released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyvault.com/toc.php5?review=1827|title=Daily Vault|last=Warburg|first=Jason|date=February 15, 2002|website=Daily Vault|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=jerry+harrison+and+Josh+Joplin+group&source=bl&ots=pV-WQ4xtHb&sig=ACfU3U2MzvZzTDuj4LH4VxMi-1n0E1WnFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj15PDHw97oAhUJLs0KHW4UCwYQ6AEwB3oECA4QKQ#v=onepage&q=jerry%20harrison%20and%20Josh%20Joplin%20group&f=false|title=Billboard|date=December 16, 2000|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Josh-Joplin-Group-Camera-One-2/release/3038187|title=Useful Music Camera One +2|last=Group|first=Josh Joplin|date=2000|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe album came out in January 30, 2001<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sperounes|first=Sandra|url=https://edmontonjournal.com|title=Ten On Tuesday|date=January 27, 2001|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindquist|first=David|url=https://www.indystar.com|title=Joplin Spins Musical Tales|date=October 11, 2001|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>to strong reviews<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Daniel|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Serves Up Useful Music|date=December 16, 2001|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/josh-joplin-group/|title=Now|last=Hughes|first=Kim|date=February 1, 2001|website=Now Toronto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and sold over 100,000 records in its first week.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schwartz|first=Daylle Deanna|title=Start And Run Your Own Record Label|publisher=Billboard Books|year=2003|isbn=0-8230-8433-7|location=NY, NY|pages=151}}</ref> It's single, \"Camera One,\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popradiotop20.com/Year/RR-HAC-2001-Year.htm|title=Hot AC Chart 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> was the first independent release to go [[List of Billboard number-one adult alternative singles of the 2000s#2000|number-one]] at Triple A radio <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Billboard_number-one_adult_alternative_singles_of_the_2000s|title=List Of Billboard #1adult alternative singles|last=Company|first=Neilson|date=March 3, 2001|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>and went to number 22 on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 chart in 2001. It won the \"Single Of The Year\" award by the [[American Association of Independent Music]]. Useful Music songs were featured in many of the top rated shows of the time, including [[Party of Five]], [[Dawson's Creek]], [[Northern Exposure]], and Camera One was a feature of an episode of the comedy series ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.\n\nJosh Joplin Group toured America, Mexico, Canada, Australia, and all of Europe. They played shows with countless bands, and artists including [[Travis (band)|Travis,]] [[Old 97's]], [[Matthew Sweet]],  [[Uncle Green]], [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse,]] [[Pink (singer)|Pink,]] [[Smoke (American band)|Smoke,]] <ref>{{Cite news|last=Harrison|first=Shane|url=|title=99x Main Stage Preview Have Your Cake|date=September 17, 1999|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gincel|first=Richard|url=|title=College Night at The High Museum|date=April 6, 1995|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>and had finished performing a German festival in Cologne, when [[Green Day]] burned the drums and stage. The band has also appeared on [[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]], [[Late Show with David Letterman]], [[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]], [[The Panel (Australian TV series)]], [[The Mike Bullard Show]], [[Viva (TV station)|Viva TV (Germany)]], [[MTV]], [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owens|first=Clay|url=https://www.stardem.com|title=The Pursuit Of Happiness|date=January 11, 2008|work=The Star-Democrat|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June of 2002, Josh Joplin began working on demos for songwriter turned producer, [[Fountains of Wayne]]'s [[Adam Schlesinger]]. Schlesinger was tapped to produce the groups sophomore Artemis release. He recorded 12 songs acoustically at [[Stratosphere Sound]], (owned by Schlesinger and [[James Iha]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513906/a-studio-a-smashing-pumpkin-can-call-home/|title=A Studio A Smashing Pumpkin Can Call Home|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|date=April 30, 1999|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  And although the timing didn't work out for the two to work together, Josh and the group, sans Davis, did end up recording   ''[[The Future That Was]].''<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scarrone|first=John|url=|title=Future That Was' One Of 2002's Best|date=January 7, 2003|work=Poughkeepsie Journal|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with Atlanta producer, Rob Gal and engineers, John Holbrook and Rudyard Lee Cullers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rob-gal-mn0000828329/credits|title=The Future That Was|last=Gal|first=Rob|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-holbrook-mn0000226375|title=The Future That Was|last=Holbrook|first=John|date=August 1, 2002|website=All Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rudyard-lee-cullers-mn0000527241|title=The Future That Was|last=Cullers|first=Rudyard Lee|date=June 1, 2002|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at Stratosphere.  On this record, the musical styles were similarly varied, ranging from slow piano- and acoustic guitar-driven pop to upbeat keyboard- and electric guitar-based rock.\n\n''The Future That Was'' received critical acclaim<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=5165&name=Josh+Joplin+Group|title=Robert Christgau Dean Of American Rock Critics|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=September 9, 2003|website=Robert Christgau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Goings On About Town|date=November 18, 2002|work=The New Yorker|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/josh-joplin/josh-joplin-group-the-future-that-was/|title=The Future That Was Review|last=Moye|first=Jay|date=April 1, 2003|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Knodel|first=Lisa|url=|title=The Future That Was (Rocked!)|date=October 4, 2002|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldridge|first=Richard|url=|title=Joplin Letting A Little Optimism Be Heard|date=September 23, 2002|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Fuller|first=Cam|url=|title=Joplin's Insight Raises The Flesh|date=April 10, 2002|work=Star Phoenix|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Leslie|first=Karl|url=|title=Josh Joplin Group Future That Was Review|date=November 28, 2002|work=St. Cloud Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/josh-joplin/|title=Josh Joplin|last=Kreicbergs|first=John|date=October 31, 2002|website=The Pitch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>but it sold poorly and Artemis released dropped the band from their contract.  Artemis released two singles from the album, \"I Am Not the Only Cowboy\" and \"Wonder Wheel,\" but neither one took off. In the fall of 2003, the band announced that it was breaking up and would play its final two shows in [[Atlanta]] in December of that year.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Josh Joplin Band===\n\n*''Projector Head''\n** Release Date: January 6,1996\n** Label: Self-released\n*''Boxing Nostalgic''\n** Release Date: April 6, 1997\n** Label: Self-released\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: May 25, 1999\n** Label: SMG Records\n\n===Josh Joplin Group===\n*''[[Useful Music]]''\n** Release Date: January 23, 2001\n** Label: [[Artemis Records]], [[Sony Music]] (Europe), [[Epic Records]] (Australia, South Africa)\n*''[[The Future That Was]]''\n** Release Date: September 24, 2002\n** Label: Artemis Records\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n", "name_user": "Brightlikethis", "label": "safe", "comment": "cite fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Joplin_Group"}
